Happy Wednesday my dudes and dudettes, during the work week and before working out I like a quick pick me up, considering my job always has me on the move.I found these Cliff bars randomly chilling on a shelf in Rite Aid. We all know Cliff bars taste like stale oats, but this one said filled with PB and anything PB is worth trying especially if you are a PB head like me. The bar is actually not that bad still that stale oat taste but loaded with some strong PB butter, and now I can get my ass back to work🏃🏽👍🏼 7/10

Laying out in beautiful #forestpark and made sure to bring my sunscreen (clearly I need a low SPF) 👏🏼☀️It's hard to believe that sunscreen used to be regulated as a simple cosmetic in the United States - FDA decided to switch it to an over the counter drug a while back (reasoning: sun exposure causes cancer) - but here is where things get interesting - Europe (known to be far more stringent across the board on ingredient safety) decided to keep it as a simple cosmetic - why? To cause research and innovation for new sunscreen ingredients since the OTC drug process (in the US and Europe) can take companies years (sometimes decades) and billions to get one new ingredient and therefore product on the market - today Europe has access to about 27 different sunscreen ingredients - but here in the United States we only have the same 8 we've been using for decades (well 16 but no one really uses half of them - one turns your skin blue 😂) - US companies have been trying to get the European sunscreen ingredients approved for use in the US because of their superiority (some since 2002) - but FDA still won't do it given these ingredients must go through the entire drug approval process - sadly this would be a good stance by FDA if the current sunscreen ingredients we use were subject to the same scrutiny but they were not - the takeaway is that we've created a situation where we are now stuck with the old ingredients (from cosmetic days) and have made it impossible to gain access to the new ones 😬🙄
